div.span: The effect runs its Reducer function, which sets the walk speed based on the parameters from the Auras.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 278px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
text-align: left

div.div: As an example, when a sword and a shield is equipped, each one applies its respective Aura which you have previously defined.

div.style: text-align: left
text-align: left

div.div: We can also pass custom parameters to the Aura to override the defaults in your definition.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 198px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
text-align: left

div.div: Effects have a function, called a Reducer, which accepts an array of values and then makes one change in the world. This is known as "reducing" many values down into one.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 208px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
text-align: left

div.div: Auras are status effects which are applied and removed by your own code. Auras can provide one or more "Effect", but each Aura can provide different parameters to the effect. The Aura determines what values to pass to the Effect.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 173px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
text-align: left

div.div: When we want to apply an Aura to an Instance, we get its Agent, which is an object that manages Auras and Effects on behalf of the given Instance.

div.div: Only one of each type of Effect can exist at a time per Agent. Effects are automatically created and removed in the update cycle, based on the current set of Auras. If two Auras provide the same Effect, then both parameters from those Auras are passed into the single Effect's reducer.

div.style: text-align: left
text-align: left

div.div: In addition to its reducer function, Effects can have a Constructor, which runs when an Aura is added that provides this Effect, and a Destructor, which is run when there are no longer any Auras providing this Effect.

div.style: text-align: left
text-align: left
div.span: For example, the WalkSpeed Effect might set the Humanoid's WalkSpeed back to the default (16) in its Destructor.
